The papers presented so far have shown novel methods of applying physiological closed-loop control to mechanical ventilation and were able to test the systems on medium/large animals or a small number of patients. The commercial availability of some of these systems has allowed clinical studies to be performed. Brogi et al. did a systematic review and meta-analysis of closed-loop systems in the clinical environment. Five studies using automated FiO2 adjustments based on SpO2 measurements and three studies investigating ventilation control (etCO2) were included in the review. The time spent in the target zone was longer for automated systems in all studies [73]. The NAVA system was evaluated in a study by Demoule et al. and compared to the ventilation with PSV. Patient-ventilator asynchrony was reduced despite not increasing the probability of remaining in a partial ventilatory mode [74]. Rose et al. did a Cochrane systematic review and meta-analysis of clinical trials comparing automated and non-automated weaning [75]. The review included 21 trials, totaling 1676 patients, and included automated systems such as SmartCare\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
